as my yoga instructor says “what’s the alternative to breathing” and so we had a little bit of time in the interim chair but i think becoming officially in the role and then really driving the organization forward i think opentable’s an amazing company and really being in position to take it to that next level of growth that next set of opportunities in front of it i’m very lucky that i got to benefit from all those years behind me where there’s a twosided marketplace it was scaled but there was all these opportunities that were still in front of it and really take it from here to there rascoff did you have establish your bonafides with the product people with engineers designers pms etc who thought of you as a finance person a cfo not a product person quarles yeah and it was a little bit of  baptism by fire because i ended up taking on the head of product role about  days after i started so i just kind of – rascoff while you were still cfo or when you became ceo quarles ceo yeah ceo so i decided to make some changes in the organization and so i took on the head of product role so actually at that time i was still cfo ceo and head of product nothing like a challenge and thankfully the background in gaming was extraordinarily helpful because it’s like product development on crack because you’re constantly – i think when i was at disney and playdom we probably launched  or  products at that point and had gone through the rapid iteration cycle something that succeeded and something that failed so it was both lots and lots of product failure and lots of product success but then lots of product launches and so i had just so many iterations and so the beauty of gaming being a hit driven industry is that there’s lots of failure to teach you rascoff and so opentable is by internet standards ancient right quarles yes rascoff i think it was started in  in the early days of the internet and so it’s quite different than a traditional startup in that sense in the sense that the product is more mature it’s been more fully built out but you have a vision for where it’s going to go so describe what will opentable be like in  or  years quarles yeah i think that’s exactly right we were started in an era when there’s literally cabling being introduced inside the restaurant because wifi didn’t exist the notion of a mobile phone wasn’t even on – flown certainly but the computer in your pocket certainly not a thing and what’s interesting is we kind of lucked out in some ways because we are the perfect marriage between technology and the physical world so we are a very local business we are in almost  restaurants around the world right now rascoff with really strong local network effects right quarles yeah and so we kind of benefitted because we really got into what i would consider the third wave of – the first wave was really all about the internet and that abstraction from location and then it was  blue links on google and now it’s like ok how to mobile and that mobile world and take advantage of that and then when i look beyond it is thinking about a world where ai machine learning are driving things and very much creating that ultimate restaurant recommendation for us where does it look like in  years i think first of all we are a much more global company today even though we’re in eight countries around the world and technically have restaurants in about  countries we’re still fairly well known in the united states and north america but not as much outside the world we’re now part of the largest travel company in the world in the form of priceline and we believe that we should be everywhere we talk about the idea of a global dining passport you wake up in berlin dubai melbourne and tokyo you should be able to have a curated mobile dining experience presented to you where you – then you can create a booking or you can go into a walk in and waitlist restaurant that’s the other side of our opportunity which is looking at market adjacencies not just fine dining reservation taking but truly broadening the aperture to look at casual opportunities as well to get a bigger chunk of our – of the dining experiences for our customers rascoff in terms of your leadership style especially early on when you first took on the ceo role is it different being a ceo  do you feel the weight of the world on your shoulders and i know i sometimes do so maybe i’m just trying to project here laughs quarles well it’s a tightrope every day in the sense that you’re always trying to – i literally have the last member of the team coming on board in the next two weeks over the last year that i’ve been trying to put in place you’re always looking at do i have the right team are they performing where they need to making sure that – rascoff so one of the first things you had to do was rebuild your team of directs quarles right exactly rascoff and you kind of rebooted the exec leadership team here quarles that’s right and there were some great folks and – but by being  years old you end up having a lot of tenure and trying to figure out what’s the right mix for where we want to go versus where we’ve been and so just getting that team in place and always kind of surveying the landscape and saying ok that’s good for maybe where we need right now but where we’re going i might need somebody else and so that was definitely a critical component i think that certainly the surprise is just how much every single word is held onto deconstructed interpreted and i’m a really honest candid open person and so i kind of put – wear everything on my sleeve and so making sure then i characterize “oh this is a direction this is just my opinion” this is just me in the kitchen just asking “oh what about this  what about this” and so making sure people understand where – what is really my driving motivation because i want to maintain that authenticity and those candid conversations but i have to be clear and people need to know when it’s not an option rascoff who’s talking i do that a lot i say like this is – i’m not saying this as ceo i’m just saying this as a user here’s a little product feedback it doesn’t mean you have to go and prioritize this bug to the top of your list it just means that i’m filing a bug approximately how many employees work at opentable quarles we’re about  employees rascoff ok and you’re part of priceline group which is tens of thousands of employees quarles sixteen thousand rascoff sixteen thousand employees quarles i think somewhere in there rascoff do most people that show up for work at opentable do they feel that they work at opentable or they work at priceline group quarles they definitely feel like they work at opentable the beauty of the structure of the priceline group is we are incredibly autonomous we run in a very individual way we even do our own tax and treasury believe it or not it’s very distributed and so – but it’s still – i come from very entrepreneurial backgrounds and so how do we make sure that we continue to make sure that the speed with which we’re operating even inside of opentable is one that is the right pace we have to have a mix though because we have a business that’s running and growing and then there’s some blank sheet stuff that we’re working on and so trying to find kind of that schizophrenia between that highly frenetic entrepreneurial go go go go how do we think about this problem it has never been done before let’s go tackle it with hey deeply operational we’re out there selling restaurants day in day out and so just trying to find people who fit on one side of that schematic versus the other rascoff so the corporate parent provides a lot of capital expertise sometimes sort of when asked it sounds like but not – quarles and frankly shielding from the public market the benefit that we have is we don’t directly communicate opentable results to the public it’s sort of put into categories and so what that enables us to do i think is play long ball with discipline many companies try many companies who are not public all these stay private forever stay private longer they all tell themselves they’re playing long ball but you don’t necessarily have discipline when you’re a private company in the way that you do as a public company as i’m sure you fully recognize we absolutely have discipline but rare is the company that can have the amazonlike freedom to just invest years at a time but i think what the beauty of the priceline group is they say look we’re going to make an investment in opentable but it’s going to be done with a heck of a lot of discipline and we’re going to make bets that might pay off in a couple years rascoff and just to give listeners perspective i think the priceline acquisition of opentable was around  billion and the market cap at priceline is  billion    billion somewhere in that range quarles yeah it could be even  rascoff so opentable is a very small part of priceline group therefore you can as you say play the long ball because you’re not going to impact the stock day to day and so priceline’s willing to make longterm investments in the future at opentable quarles although as they point out booking is obviously the behemoth in the group it still matters whether i beat my numbers or not and so it’s more around the expectation of conscious investment but i very much have to beat the numbers but i think it is an opportunity to say “hey yeah we’re not the largest part of the group for certain but dining is a  trillion market how do you dream really big and be in position to take on a much bigger chunk of the market than we currently are today” rascoff i’ve been a big proponent of dualclass stock which zillow group has which allows us to play long ball at zillow group and not worry as much about nearterm stock price volatility because it’s founder controlled but being part of a much larger entity is another hack to allow a company like opentable to be longterm oriented let’s talk about rebuilding your management team when you came in how many people have you hired among your direct reports how many direct reports do you have what were you looking for as you rebuilt that team and did you do it sort of serially like you wanted to – you hired one and then saw how that person fit on the team and then the next and the next or you went for several people at once quarles there’s a couple things that i did first of all hiring is incredibly challenging it’s a full time job you’re out there always and i think there is little known about what my ambition was for opentable and so if you were just getting the call kind of blind you were going “oh opentable yeah they went public what happened” and there wasn’t necessarily an understanding of where – so a lot of it was sort of internal pr and trying to just get people to recognize what the opportunity and ambition was in terms of how you go about it you try – i ended up trying to look for both a cfo and i split the product role into two we had kind of a head of product overall but the restaurant product and the consumer product are vastly different rascoff the restaurant part meaning the software that restaurants use quarles yeah and it’s basically – it’s a bb saas product with – that’s essentially part inventory management almost like a saver and part crm and so the skill set needed there really different from a traditional consumer product background so i ended up looking for all three of those roles at the same time which was not easy or awesome laughter rascoff how did employees handle that they had a new ceo and they knew there were other leadership changes coming  was that – quarles again i had all the hats so i guess that’s good and bad and so – and then i’ve also – have a new head of hr people and culture as we call it here at opentable starting in two weeks and then we elevated some of our sales and our internal folks into more senior roles inside the company there’s been a mix and shift of all of it and i think the challenge is each person you add and subtract changes the alchemy of that group and one of the things that i really wanted to do when i first came in i’m a very much a radical candor as my friend kim scott will attest to who wrote the book on that but it’s – i think it was my first week taking over the team and we were talking about what we were working on for the next i think board meeting and i said “ok now disagree with me” and everyone was silent and so i think i’ve now created a culture where people feel very comfortable speaking up and reaching out but it has to be a safe environment where they feel like “hey i can exercise my opinion i can disagree but i’m not going to be impugned for doing so” and each new person you add you’ve got to test the chemistry of how that’s going to work and the dynamic and it’s a little scary i’ll say every time you add a new person because you just never quite know as much as the interviewing process is helpful it never really gives you that sense of everybody at once and that’s the biggest challenge in making sure that that the norms of the groups are – the group are understood and frankly appreciated and respected rascoff isn’t it amazing that no matter how much technology there is in our businesses at the end of the day it’s still all about people right quarles until the machines take over the humans – we’re an interesting lot and we don’t always behave at least visually rationally i’m sure it’s rational underneath but it’s hard because you’re managing people’s ambitions and they’re bringing their family and their lives into the office every single day and so you’re trying to make that blend work and where are they in their stage of career and how long have they been here and all those different factors weigh in to how they’re going to – what person they’re bringing to the office that day rascoff you’ve touched on several themes that i’m pretty passionate about the importance of encouraging dissent is something that i talk about a lot radical candor we actually had one of the coauthors come and speak at our exec offsite and the point is that you show someone that you care and then you’re radically candid with them so that that’s the best way to provide feedback and it’s something that we preach at zillow for sure you said something really interesting you said each person that you add or subtract to that leadership team changes the chemistry changes the alchemy of the group have you had situations in your career here or elsewhere where somebody perhaps was a high performer sort of on a different team and they still have the same skill set but they don’t perform well with this other team because of the chemistry quarles yeah it happened actually when were at playdom we had a pretty wellfunctioning group and then we added a new leader role in that group and i think what was challenging was it was a very different style than that person was used to operating in and had been at very large companies where sometimes the political game was more important and it was disruptive and i saw it happening kind of in real time and i think i want to be conscious to – the beauty of it is when you’re in the leadership role it’s fully in your power and control to prevent that from happening and so if you see even hints of behaviors that you don’t think are advantageous to that group functioning well you tamp them out and you tamp them out quickly and i think that’s that key is – the beauty of being in that role you have the power to change the dynamics and really set the norms but i have seen it and it can be destructive  i think it can create side conversations inside negotiations and discussions that then people aren’t necessarily bringing their whole honest selves into the room and i think the group decision making suffers as a result rascoff yeah i’ve seen situations where somebody – their chemistry with the rest of the team worked well in one particular role and they move into some other role or the team around them changes and they’re no longer successful the other thing i’ve seen kind of the corollary to that is a particular management style works that that person has works well when the business is in a particular state let’s say a person oversees three or four different parts of the business and everything is going pretty well and so they’re managing kind of at  feet and then one of the areas of those – of that business does not perform well and it’s time for them to go down to – into the trenches and they don’t do a good job transitioning between those two states it’s interesting because the person’s skill set hasn’t changed they have all the same intellect the same energy passion whatever but they were successful in one – at one point in time and they’re no longer successful at another quarles the key question i always ask in there is your work avoidance what are the things that you hate doing in your job and in that situation if you’re not good at going down deep then you better find a strategy so that you don’t have to and so you better make sure people are around you and you make sure succession planning is thought through because if you’re put in a position where you’re having to do the part of your job that you frankly hate you’re not going to be good at it you’re not going to enjoy it and temporary is one thing but if you – you better have a strategy around that i’m always asking people what part of your job you hate there’s always a part of your job you hate so then what are your strategies for mitigation how do you get around that and if those strategies fail like somebody leaves and now they’re having to dive in then it’s a signal to me that they’re going to have some challenges and they haven’t thought through or don’t understand frankly what those weaknesses are because it’s all about self awareness rascoff this is as another one of my management tenets is that when people aren’t doing their job effectively it’s usually not because they don’t have the particular skill set to do that job well it’s because of a low level of engagement because they’re not fired up about that particular role at that point in time in theory you’ve done a good enough job screening them for their skill set on the way in there are exceptions obviously but it’s more about making sure that they’re engaged in that particular role and a key way to improve engagement is to try to remove things that they don’t like doing from their job let’s talk about innovation this is a company that again was started in  and i worry about this a lot at zillow we started in  so we’re now in our second decade most tech companies lose a step in their – at the end of their first decade and they lose two or three steps in their second decade and most of them falter and there are very few category leaders that are ten or more years old opentable has benefited from its really strong network effect you have a lot of restaurants that gets a lot of diners you have a lot of diners that gets a lot of restaurants and network effects are notoriously difficult to disrupt but that could also create a lazy environment where you’re not being forced into it because you don’t feel like you’re under constant attack so how do you maintain innovation with a company that’s been around as long as opentable quarles yeah and i would say opentable did wait a little too long to modernize its overall stack for example it was a monolithic code base up until  and now a lot of that work has been done to chop it up into a service oriented architecture and we can ship every day which was so not the case even several years ago if you start thinking about rapid iterative ab testing culture that was something that wasn’t even possible technically inside the organization just a handful of years ago that has been really important to kind of transition that all i think but continuing to look forward and say okay what are the new ways forward for our business obviously mobile is the majority of our dining activity now that’s happening in those devices and what’s interesting is we’re seeing entirely different use cases appear because i know where you are i know what’s available near you and so this whole dining within the hour is a brand new use case that didn’t even exist several years ago before the mobile device came to be i think the cool thing is when i do look forward and thinking about an ai driven world and where machine learning is going and how do our data science teams learn and iterate and operate so one area is just i want to create the ultimate restaurant recommendation engine the most frustrating thing is you go and you go like “oh i want to go to restaurant x” and it’s booked up or something or it’s maybe not even on the opentable network although there are very few restaurants that are not on opentable and you should all be on opentable but it’s still saying “oh i know where that restaurant’s located  i know the price point i know the menu items i know all this information all this signal and i hopefully know something about you at this point i know what your preferences have been i know where you’ve dined in the past how do i create recommendations specifically for you” rascoff what about payments how important is payments to your innovation so being able to get up from the table at the end of a meal and have opentable pay quarles yeah we have dabbled a lot and we’ve innovated a lot in payments and i’m on my now third iteration on the payment i would say on payments in general and i think anytime you look at financial innovation you see these really slow adoption curves and then eventually it kinks up look at atm adoption even online banking adoption and i still contend that we’re in year two of the seven year journey on mobile payments rascoff is it harder to get the restaurants on board or the diners quarles it’s harder to get the restaurants on board and primarily because they’re wedded to a point of sale system so they have micros primarily in the united states and other countries it’s a different point of sale system and there’s just not a lot of motivation to integrate the point of sale so that’s been the challenge and so we’ve tried a number things we tried the full on point of sale integration just because i think we’ve also tried to go around the point of sale system we had a product called opentable tab that we were trying to understand and see is that the right solution we’re now looking and saying ok is there another way to get into point of sale apple pay has just hit its two year anniversary and i think still trying to make progress i do believe though when you’ve experienced an opentable pay restaurant it is magic it is magic you’re sitting there you can see the items showing up in your phone and then – and it just happened to me the other day i had to go i had a meeting i had to get to and i just hit the bar slide it over and i’m good to go and there’s no dance at the end of the dining people want that uberization in the restaurant experience they want to not be wed to – but its how do i get all the infrastructure in place to actually get it accomplished  we’re looking at how do we do that and we’re making progress but i always wish it was faster rascoff it’s interesting when i asked about innovation you immediately went to the importance of making sure that the technology is serviceoriented allows for rapid iteration and it sounds like you probably went through a big rearchitecture to enable that did you find other parts of the organization like hr pr social media consumer marketing finance even all of the sudden became more innovative when they saw a product team that was able to ship code daily weekly instead of every quarter or two and there was more product innovation happening for the consumer now all of the sudden these other nontechnical parts of the organization started being more innovative quarles well and i think it goes into just the – and the importance of data frankly and it’s that line if you have data bring the data if we’re using opinion let’s use mine i’ve encouraged every single department here to know your data and so if you’re in hr you should know who are the employees where are they going what’s the retention rate of our employees if it’s in finance you better know your numbers and data but just across the board and how data plays into this role of we – our pm sounds like “we don’t know if it’s going to work” obviously i have a point of view but we’re often surprised and so being in position to let the data help show you the way how do you steer the whole company to getting and receiving analyzing and knowing their data when i’m in a meeting and i ask a fairly simple question i think and somebody can’t get the answer quickly it’s a bad sign for me it’s like uhoh they don’t know their business they don’t know their data and then i ask “well why can’t you is it hard to get are we not looking at those” one of the things i’m trying to do is we were all about the reservation and we spent very little time thinking about what happened before the reservation all the tagging of activity of just user behavior prior to a reservation hadn’t really been focused on and so we weren’t even collecting the data in some instances so how were we going to help drive discovery when we don’t even know what’s happening prior to the reservation getting a whole lot more kind of on people to kind of understand what those preconditions are to what ultimately makes us money here which is that connection between the restaurant and the diner rascoff is there anything you would have done differently thinking now back on your first year as ceo if you knew then what you know now anything that you would have changed quarles i don’t know if i would have taken on so many jobs at once frankly it was not good for my sleep or gray hair to be honest it was hard on me and so i might have been measured and part of it is when i feel like it’s not going to work i just en